# Architecture Audit Mode

## Living sync (during implementation)

Living-audit documents (`docs/audit/**`, per-folder audit `README.md` files listed in [docs/audit/INDEX.md](docs/audit/INDEX.md)) are **protected** — see [`.cursor/rules/protected-documentation.mdc`](.cursor/rules/protected-documentation.mdc).

When code changes affect living documentation:

1. **Identify** which audit docs or maintained README sections require updates (use [docs/audit/INDEX.md](docs/audit/INDEX.md) and [docs/audit/MAINTENANCE.md](docs/audit/MAINTENANCE.md)).
2. **If the user has explicitly authorized** those documentation edits in the current task — update only the impacted sections in the same task per MAINTENANCE. If the user cites `@audit path#section`, edit that section first.
3. **If authorization has not been given** — leave protected files unchanged; report the required documentation updates (file paths and sections); request explicit user approval before editing.

An instruction to “keep audits updated” does **not** override protected-file approval unless the task explicitly authorizes the affected files or defined documentation scope.

Cross-cutting updates when relevant and authorized: `docs/audit/DUPLICATES.md`, `docs/audit/EXECUTION_TRACES.md`.

## Audit-only pass (explicit request)

When the user asks for an architecture **audit** (not a feature), follow [docs/process/architecture_audit_mode.md](docs/process/architecture_audit_mode.md):

- DO NOT modify application code.
- Document the code as it exists today.
- If uncertain: **Unknown from static analysis.**

## Standard README sections

Purpose, Files, Entry Points, Dependencies, Runtime Usage, Possible Dead Code, Notes, Per-file inventory, Execution traces.

Accuracy over speed in audit-only mode; surgical section updates in living sync mode when documentation edits are explicitly authorized.
